  "命令行参数从哪来": "Where command-line arguments come from",
  "你在终端敲 ./tool hello 42，shell 会按空格把这行拆成三个「词」：./tool、hello、42。操作系统启动你的程序时，把这些词整理成一个字符串数组交给 main——这就是 argv（argument vector）。词的总数交给 argc（argument count）。注意第 0 个永远是程序自己被调用的名字，真正的用户参数从 argv[1] 开始。C 不像高级语言有现成的解析库，所有命令行处理都从读懂这两个形参开始。": "When you type ./tool hello 42 in a terminal, the shell splits the line by spaces into three \"words\": ./tool, hello, 42. As the OS starts your program, it packs those words into an array of strings handed to main — this is argv (argument vector). The total count goes into argc (argument count). Note that index 0 is always the name the program was invoked with; real user arguments start at argv[1]. Unlike high-level languages, C has no built-in parsing library, so all command-line work begins by reading these two parameters.",
